      <hedline>
        <hl1>Is Divorce Truly a Salvation?</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>David Brenner letter disputes Jane Smiley's September 12 Op-Ed article on divorce</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Jane Smiley (Op-Ed, Sept. 12) implies that there is more divorce because people now live longer, saying that in the past, ''death did the work of divorce.'' But social science research has disproved this theory.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Jane Smiley (Op-Ed, Sept. 12) implies that there is more divorce because people now live longer, saying that in the past, ''death did the work of divorce.'' But social science research has disproved this theory.</p>
        <p>Most of the increase in longevity today is due to lower rates of infant and child mortality, a medical advance that has no effect on divorce rates. Life expectancy from the median age of marriage has increased only one year for men and less than five months for women since 1960, hardly long enough to exert much influence either way on decisions to divorce.</p>
        <p>DAVID BRENNER  Associate Director  Institute for American Values  New York, Sept. 12, 2000</p>
      </block>
